{"id":"2205.14768","submitter":"Gonzalo Contreras","authors":"Fernando Oliveira and Gonzalo Contreras","title":"No elliptic points from fixed prime ends","comments":null,"journal-ref":null,"doi":null,"report-no":null,"categories":"math.DS","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  We consider area preserving maps of surfaces and extend Mather's result on\nthe equality of the closure of the four branches of saddles. He assumed\nelliptic fixed points to be Moser stable, while we require only that the\nderivative at this points to be a rotation by an angle different from zero.\nThere are many results in the literature which require the hypothesis that\nelliptic periodic points be Moser stable that now can be extended to the case\nthat the derivative at these points be an irrational rotation. The key point is\nto give more information on Cartwright and Littlewood's fixed point theorem, to\nshow that the fixed point obtained by a fixed prime end can not be elliptic.\nHypotheses then became easier to verify: non degeneracy of fixed points and\nnonexistence of saddle connections. As an application we show that the result\nimmediately implies that for the standard map family, for all values of the\nparameter, except one, the principal hyperbolic fixed point has homoclinic\npoints. We also extend results to surfaces with boundary in order to be\napplicable to return maps to surfaces of section and broken book\ndecompositions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 29 May 2022 21:09:43 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Fri, 6 Jan 2023 21:38:37 GMT"}],"update_date":"2023-01-10"}
